2 INTRODUCED BY B. BARKER, C. KEOGH
3
4 A JOINT RESOLUTION OF THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF
5 MONTANA REQUESTING AN INTERIM STUDY ON IMPROVING SCHOOL SAFETY; AND REQUIRING
6 THAT THE FINAL RESULTS OF THE STUDY BE REPORTED TO THE 70TH LEGISLATURE.
7
8 WHEREAS, the safety of children and the adults who educate and care for them is of paramount
9 importance;
10 WHEREAS, there is a strong correlation between a safe school environment and higher academic
11 achievement, with students in safer schools tending to have better grades and test scores; and
12 WHEREAS, safe schools promote positive social interactions, reduce bullying, and create a more
13 supportive environment for students to develop healthy relationships; and
14 WHEREAS, students who feel secure at school are more likely to be engaged in their learning and
15 actively participate in school activities; and
16 WHEREAS, Montana K-12 schools would benefit from a coordinated cross-system collaborative study
17 to identify existing and nonexistent school safety practices; and
18 WHEREAS, having proper safety protocols in place allows for effective collaborative response to
19 emergencies such as fires, medical emergencies, and active shooter scenarios; and
20 WHEREAS, Montana is one of the few states without a unified, coordinated approach to supporting
21 school safety and lacks a designated state system that provides schools with comprehensive guidance and
22 support.
23
24 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF
25 THE STATE OF MONTANA:
26 That the Legislative Council be requested to designate an appropriate interim committee or statutory
27 committee, pursuant to section 5-5-217, MCA, to conduct a study on improving school safety.
28 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the committee collaborate in this study with relevant stakeholders,
